[2026-07-05T02:00:00] TASK 4A — PIVOT (post-adversarial-review fixes, BLOCKING + SIGNIFICANT)
Adversarial review (logs/adversarial-generalist.build.log, "TASK 4A
REVIEW") found one BLOCKING and one SIGNIFICANT issue, both confirmed
real and both fixed — this overrides tester's prior "gate met" verdict
per BuildPlan's precedence rule.

**BLOCKING — mid-narration decisions never called
`speechSynthesis.cancel()`.** `App.tsx`'s `decide()` (the §11.4 decision
function) only called `playback.resetForNewPaper()` — a Zustand store
write that flips the UI's *displayed* `isPlaying`/highlight state but
never touches `usePlaybackEngine`'s own live utterance/refs
(`statusRef`/`generationRef`/`currentUtteranceRef`). SPEC.md §6.6
explicitly requires the real `cancel()` synchronously as part of the
decision ("no audible overlap between papers"); without it, the old
paper's narration kept speaking uninterrupted, and once it eventually
finished, the engine's own generation-guard didn't catch it (generation
only bumps on `play()`/`pause()`/`cancel()`, none of which `decide()`
called), so a stale `onFinished` could fire against `itemsRef.current`
already pointing at the *new* paper — silently auto-deciding a paper the
user never heard. This also broke the codebase's own established
invariant (documented in `usePlaybackEngine.ts`/`playbackStore.ts`) that
the engine is the sole source of truth for playback state and the store
is a read-only reflection — `resetForNewPaper()` was writing the store
out of band.
Fix: reordered `App.tsx` so `usePlaybackEngine` is constructed before
`decide()` (bridging the reverse dependency — `onFinished`'s auto-decide
path needs to call `decide()`, which needs `engine.cancel` — via a
`decideRef` ref updated in an effect, avoiding a circular
`useCallback`). `decide()` now calls `engine.cancel()` synchronously as
its first line, and no longer calls `playback.resetForNewPaper()` at
all — `cancel()` already drives `isPlaying` back to `false` (via the
existing engine-status-mirroring effect) and the highlighted segment
back to `null` (via `cancel()`'s own `onItemChange(null)` call), so the
store needs no separate out-of-band write; this restores the "engine is
the one source of truth" invariant rather than just papering over the
symptom.
Test added: `App.test.tsx`'s new `describe('mid-narration decisions call
the playback engine's cancel() (§6.6)')` — mocks the whole
`usePlaybackEngine` module (`vi.mock`) so the test can assert `App.tsx`'s
own `decide()` closure calls the *real* exported `cancel()` function
synchronously (no `waitFor`, matching §6.6's synchronous requirement),
independent of the real hook's internal mechanics (which have their own
separate, already-existing coverage in `usePlaybackEngine.test.ts`).
Two cases: decide-while-playing calls `cancel()` exactly once
synchronously; decide-while-idle also calls it (documented as correct,
simplest-to-reason-about behavior — `cancel()` is cheap/idempotent, and
calling it unconditionally is what makes the invariant hold regardless
of what `App.tsx` *thinks* the status is).

**SIGNIFICANT — `useSwipeToDecide`'s own `disabled` re-entrancy guard
was dead code.** The hook documented and unit-tested a `disabled` option
specifically to stop a fast double-swipe from firing two decisions for
the same paper, but `StackScreen.tsx` called `useSwipeToDecide({
onDecide })` with no `disabled` argument, and its own props interface
had no field for `App.tsx` to thread `updateDecision.isPending` through
— so the guard never actually engaged against a real double input, and
the backend has no idempotency check of its own either (`update_decision`
unconditionally overwrites).
Fix, two layers (matching the reviewer's ask plus one additional
defense-in-depth layer): (1) added `StackScreen`'s new
`isDecisionPending?: boolean` prop, threaded straight into
`useSwipeToDecide`'s `disabled` option; `App.tsx` passes
`updateDecision.isPending`. (2) Added a synchronous internal
`hasDecidedRef` guard inside `useSwipeToDecide` itself (same pattern/
reason as `usePlaybackEngine.ts`'s own `statusRef` fix from Task 2D's
post-review round): a React state prop like `isPending` hasn't
necessarily committed between two input events landing in the same
tick (two fast keydowns, a double-tap, or a synchronous test firing two
triggers back to back), so a plain ref read/written synchronously inside
`commitExit` closes that gap regardless of render timing — this is the
primary guard; `disabled`/`isPending` is the secondary, real-world
"already in flight to the server" signal. Also added `key={pmid}` to
`App.tsx`'s `<StackScreen>` so each card gets a fresh
`StackScreen`/`useSwipeToDecide` instance (matching real per-card
semantics — the guard is scoped to one card's lifetime, not carried
across cards without an explicit reset mechanism).
Tests added: `useSwipeToDecide.test.ts`'s new "re-entrancy: a single
instance never commits a second decision" describe block (two rapid
`triggerDecision` calls / a drag-commit immediately followed by a tap /
a committed decision permanently blocking any later call on the same
instance — all in one `act()` block, i.e. genuinely the same tick).
`StackScreen.test.tsx`'s new "never fires a second decision for the
same card" and "does not commit... while isDecisionPending is true"
cases.
Test-suite fallout from adding the guard (expected, not a regression):
three pre-existing tests had been calling multiple *sequential*
decisions on the *same* hook/component instance to compare swipe vs.
tap vs. keyboard call shapes — exactly the pattern the new guard now
correctly blocks, since real usage never does this (a card is decided
once, then a fresh instance mounts for the next one via `key={pmid}`).
Rewrote `useSwipeToDecide.test.ts`'s two "same call shape across input
methods" tests and `StackScreen.test.tsx`'s "routes tap and keyboard
decisions through the same onDecide callback" test to use a fresh
`renderHook`/`render` (with explicit `.unmount()` between `document`-
level-keydown-listening renders, to avoid duplicate-listener/duplicate-
DOM cross-talk) per input method instead of reusing one instance — this
is a corrected assumption in the tests, not a functional regression;
each input method is still proven to produce the identical `onDecide`
call shape.

